Compile instructions:
To compile manually, run: g++ -Wall -Wextra -std=c++17 -o xsh main.cpp command.cpp exec.cpp
or, use Makefile:
    - In terminal, cd to directory containing Makefile, in this case, a2: cd ~/a2
    - To clean Makefile, run: make clean
    - To run Makefile, run: make

Operating instructions:
- Ensure you are in the directory containing all of your files, in this case, a2
- To run program, run: ./xsh
- The program will display a prompt using the current username, such as: cssc3154%
- To test, type a valid command
- To exit shell, type: exit

Valid test commands:
- ls: tests running one command with no argument
- ls -la: tests running one command with one argument
- ls | sort: tests one pipe
- ls -la | sort -fi: tests one pipe with arguments
- ls -la | sort -fi | grep .bashrc: tests multiple pipes
- /usr/bin/echo printme: tests full executable path with one argument
- exit: tests built-in exit command

Invalid test commands:
- ls -la -h: rejects more than one argument
- ls |: rejects a missing command after a pipe
- | sort: rejects a missing command before a pipe
- ls | sort -fi extra: rejects more than one argument in a piped command
- exit now: rejects invalid exit format

List/description of novel/significant design decisions:
- main.cpp C++ file for the main shell loop of the program
- command.cpp C++ file for creating prompt, parsing user input, and checking valid commands
- exec.cpp C++ file for creating child processes, executing commands, and handling pipes
- xsh.h Header file to declare ParsedCommand struct
- Makefile to compile program and create executable xsh
- README file to instruct use of program
- exec.cpp uses fork(), execvp(), pipe(), dup2(), close(), and waitpid().

Description of any extra features/algorithms/functionality you included which were not required:
- No additional features were included.

Description of all known deficiencies or bugs:
- The shell only supports the specific valid commands required by the assignment. Any invalid commands are given an error message.

Division of Work:
-
-

Lessons Learned:
- We learned how a basic shell reads user commands and runs programs.
- We learned how fork() creates a child process and execvp() runs a new program inside that child process.
- We learned how pipe() and dup2() connect commands so the output of a command becomes the input of another.
- We learned how waitpid() lets the parent wait for child processes to finish before prompting again.